		"name": "API-Custom-Variables",
		"description": "This collection demonstrates the use of **Postman variables** using a **Custom API** (`http://localhost:3000`).\n\n### Variable Types Covered (with explanations):\n\n- **Global Variables**  \n    Accessible across all workspaces, collections, and requests.  \n    **Example**: `global_customURL` is stored as a **global variable**.\n    \n- **Environment Variables**  \n    Scoped to a specific environment and commonly used for environment-specific values.  \n    **Example**: `env_customURL` is stored as an **environment variable**.\n    \n- **Collection Variables**  \n    Available only within the collection and ideal for shared values across requests.  \n    **Example**: `coll_id` is stored as a **collection variable**.\n    \n- **Local Variables**  \n    Available only during the execution of a single request and defined using scripts.  \n    **Example**: `local_url` is set as a **local variable** in the **Pre-request Script**.\n    \n\n**Additional Features:**\n\n- Demonstrates how to **set and unset variables** using scripts.\n    \n\n### Create Your Own API Using JSON Server\n\n1. **Install Node.js** on your system.\n    \n2. commands to check version of node and npm\n    \n    1. `node --version`\n        \n    2. `npm --version`\n        \n3. install json server `npm install -g json-server`\n    \n4. Create a **sample JSON file** (for example: `students.json`) with mock data.\n    \n5. Open the **command prompt** in the folder where the JSON file is located.\n    \n6. `json-server students.json`\n    \n7. JSON Server will automatically create REST API endpoints, allowing you to **perform CRUD operations** (Create, Read, Update, Delete).",
		"schema": "https://schema.getpostman.com/json/collection/v2.1.0/collection.json",
		"_exporter_id": "21963655"
	},
